WEBVTT

00:03.404 --> 00:07.341
In September, 2017,
Hurricane Maria devastated

00:07.375 --> 00:09.843
the American island
of Puerto Rico.

00:09.877 --> 00:13.214
At the time of this writing
12 days after the hurricane,

00:13.247 --> 00:15.716
almost 95% of the island's
residents

00:15.749 --> 00:17.351
are still without power,

00:17.385 --> 00:20.688
and close to half don't have
clean water.

00:20.721 --> 00:22.690
Just months prior, we shot an
episode there

00:22.723 --> 00:25.526
hoping to capture the
staggering economic crisis

00:25.559 --> 00:28.362
that Puerto Ricans were
already dealing with.

00:28.396 --> 00:30.764
So now we have to ask ourselves,

00:30.798 --> 00:33.101
can the island ever rebuild,

00:33.134 --> 00:36.204
and what is our responsibility
as Americans

00:36.237 --> 00:39.073
in making that a reality?

00:40.308 --> 00:42.076
♪ I took a walk

00:42.110 --> 00:45.846
♪ Through this beautiful world ♪

00:45.879 --> 00:50.884
♪ Felt the cool rain
on my shoulder ♪

00:50.918 --> 00:57.391
♪ Found something good
in this beautiful world ♪

00:57.425 --> 01:01.895
♪ I felt the rain
getting colder ♪

01:01.929 --> 01:03.631
♪

01:03.664 --> 01:06.300
♪ Sha la la la

01:06.334 --> 01:09.370
♪ Sha la la la la la

01:09.403 --> 01:12.540
♪ Sha la la la la

01:12.573 --> 01:17.311
♪ Sha la la la la la la

01:23.117 --> 01:25.286
It's the American dream, right?

01:29.022 --> 01:31.492
What so many of us work for,

01:31.525 --> 01:37.298
sell our labor
or pieces of our souls for:

01:37.331 --> 01:40.100
an island in the sun...

01:41.769 --> 01:43.771
Preferably one
where they speak English

01:43.804 --> 01:46.907
and the dollar is accepted
everywhere.

01:48.442 --> 01:51.479
Puerto Rico:
it's America, right?

01:51.512 --> 01:55.916
It's ours,
and we've held on to it,

01:55.949 --> 01:58.186
fiercely at times, since 1898

01:58.219 --> 02:00.288
after taking it by force

02:00.321 --> 02:02.089
during the Spanish-American War.

02:02.122 --> 02:04.792
♪

02:07.828 --> 02:11.098
♪

02:11.131 --> 02:12.466
I want to take you

02:12.500 --> 02:14.168
to one of worst-performing
economies

02:14.202 --> 02:15.303
in the developed world.

02:15.336 --> 02:17.205
$73 billion debt...

02:17.238 --> 02:19.106
The employment rate is only 35%.

02:19.139 --> 02:21.975
Highest sales tax of any
United States jurisdiction,

02:22.009 --> 02:23.177
11.5%.

02:23.211 --> 02:24.845
45% live in poverty.

02:24.878 --> 02:27.181
Biggest municipal bankruptcy
in U.S. history.

02:27.215 --> 02:28.649
Over the last ten years,
more than

02:28.682 --> 02:32.186
5% of the population has fled.

02:35.856 --> 02:38.826
But what's it like
for Puerto Ricans,

02:38.859 --> 02:40.661
for the people who live here,

02:40.694 --> 02:43.030
whose families have lived here
for generations?

02:43.063 --> 02:46.467
Many have left for
an easier life in the States.

02:46.500 --> 02:50.238
More keep leaving...
but not all.

02:51.672 --> 02:53.707
What do you write about
most of the time?

02:53.741 --> 02:55.175
What do you cover?

02:55.209 --> 02:56.977
Right now, I'm covering
a lot of politics.

02:57.010 --> 03:00.214
Journalist Hermes Ayala
is one of those diehards

03:00.248 --> 03:01.382
who's sticking it out.

03:01.415 --> 03:03.484
The more I've done

03:03.517 --> 03:06.520
investigative and political
journalism in Puerto Rico,

03:06.554 --> 03:09.223
the more I feel
a responsibility to stay here

03:09.257 --> 03:11.191
and help out my nation.

03:14.562 --> 03:17.931
♪

03:17.965 --> 03:19.433
So this is Santurce.

03:19.467 --> 03:20.868
Somebody called it
on the way over

03:20.901 --> 03:22.370
the art district?

03:22.403 --> 03:24.238
This is sort of an art district,

03:24.272 --> 03:26.340
but this was a barrio
that was founded

03:26.374 --> 03:28.276
by freed black slaves, right?

03:28.309 --> 03:29.743
♪

03:29.777 --> 03:31.545
Going through tons
of transformations,

03:31.579 --> 03:35.483
like every working-class
neighborhood.

03:37.117 --> 03:39.052
Some people think
that Puerto Rico

03:39.086 --> 03:40.454
takes advantage of the States,

03:40.488 --> 03:42.055
but it's a two-way street.

03:42.089 --> 03:44.258
- Right?
- You know?

03:44.292 --> 03:45.726
Right there.

03:45.759 --> 03:47.761
This is my friend Laura
right here.

03:47.795 --> 03:49.196
- Hi, Laura.
- Hi.

03:49.229 --> 03:50.424
- How are you?
- Nice to meet you.

03:50.431 --> 03:51.965
Like everyone here, Hermes

03:51.999 --> 03:53.801
and fellow journalist
Laura Moscoso

03:53.834 --> 03:55.603
are trying to make sense
of a situation

03:55.636 --> 03:58.306
that seems Kafka-esque at best.

03:58.339 --> 04:00.808
So dumb question.
What is Puerto Rico?

04:00.841 --> 04:02.476
It's not a state.

04:02.510 --> 04:04.312
It's kind of like a colony,
but it's not.

04:04.345 --> 04:06.079
It's not kind.
It is.

04:06.113 --> 04:07.448
It is a colony.

04:07.481 --> 04:09.417
It's an unincorporated
territory.

04:09.450 --> 04:10.984
"Unincorporated territory."

04:11.018 --> 04:12.620
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

04:12.653 --> 04:14.922
So, you know, what's that?
What is that?

04:14.955 --> 04:17.925
We're still trying to
figure out sometimes, you know?

04:17.958 --> 04:19.726
Would you say the majority
of Puerto Ricans

04:19.760 --> 04:21.762
consider themselves Americans?

04:21.795 --> 04:23.790
Or do they consider themselves
Puerto Ricans or both?

04:23.797 --> 04:26.133
I think that they
consider theirself Puerto Ricans

04:26.166 --> 04:29.670
with the privilege of having
the United States citizenship.

04:29.703 --> 04:31.772
Yeah, but it's kind of
a half-ass citizenship.

04:31.805 --> 04:32.940
Can't vote for president.

04:32.973 --> 04:34.241
Nor Congress.

04:34.274 --> 04:35.476
- Or Congress.
- Anything.

04:35.509 --> 04:36.910
You don't really have much voice

04:36.944 --> 04:38.346
in your own destiny.

04:38.379 --> 04:40.013
Exactly.
You can only go to war.

04:40.047 --> 04:41.949
That's the only thing
that you can do with right.

04:41.982 --> 04:47.020
Right. But Puerto Rico owes,
what, $75 billion right now?

04:47.054 --> 04:48.856
- 72, yeah.
- 72.

04:48.889 --> 04:50.190
I don't see statehood.

04:50.223 --> 04:52.192
I don't see Congress or Senate
ever...

04:52.225 --> 04:53.594
Me neither.

04:53.627 --> 04:57.197
Ever taking on
a $72 billion debt load,

04:57.230 --> 04:59.132
especially for a lot of people
who speak Spanish.

04:59.166 --> 05:00.434
Exactly.

05:00.468 --> 05:02.169
What's the way out of this?

05:02.202 --> 05:04.472
Oh, my God.

05:04.505 --> 05:06.106
What about tourism?

05:06.139 --> 05:07.975
It's an industry of services

05:08.008 --> 05:10.544
to service the wealthy.

05:10.578 --> 05:13.146
And then at the same time,
you take $450 million

05:13.180 --> 05:14.815
out of the university,
for example,

05:14.848 --> 05:17.551
so you're gonna have
less educated people

05:17.585 --> 05:20.220
willing to do any type
of work...

05:20.253 --> 05:21.855
To survive.

05:21.889 --> 05:24.324
You are not really
producing an economy

05:24.358 --> 05:27.327
that a person can survive in,
you know?

05:27.361 --> 05:29.797
This is a country
where people live,

05:29.830 --> 05:31.298
where we do things.

05:31.331 --> 05:34.502
And we have culture
and literature and music

05:34.535 --> 05:36.970
and produce intellectual,
important work.

05:37.004 --> 05:41.074
They are selling us
as only a good resort

05:41.108 --> 05:45.579
to have a piña colada
in the beach and that's it.

05:45.613 --> 05:48.181
We actually invented
piña coladas, so...

05:52.686 --> 05:57.858
Even though we are, like,
getting over by...

05:57.891 --> 06:00.528
- Vultures.
- Yeah, a lot of vultures.

06:00.561 --> 06:03.096
The people of Puerto Rico
are good people,

06:03.130 --> 06:07.635
and I think that we are gonna
get past this.

06:14.475 --> 06:17.077
The situation here
is truly grave.

06:17.110 --> 06:19.880
So how exactly did Puerto Rico
find itself

06:19.913 --> 06:24.051
so deeply and seemingly
irrevocably screwed?

06:25.953 --> 06:27.721
In the early '70s,

06:27.755 --> 06:29.590
things were looking
pretty good for Puerto Rico.

06:29.623 --> 06:31.725
A tax incentive was introduced,

06:31.759 --> 06:34.728
which helped lure dozens of
major companies to the island,

06:34.762 --> 06:37.731
employing significant numbers
of people.

06:40.601 --> 06:43.437
But when that incentive
expired in 2006,

06:43.471 --> 06:46.039
concurrent with a major
recession in the States,

06:46.073 --> 06:49.142
those companies packed up
and left.

06:49.176 --> 06:51.244
Thousands of Puerto Ricans
followed,

06:51.278 --> 06:56.884
looking for jobs that no
longer existed on the island.

06:56.917 --> 06:59.453
The tax base shrunk drastically,

06:59.487 --> 07:01.455
creating a dire need for cash

07:01.489 --> 07:04.758
to shore up basic needs
and services.

07:04.792 --> 07:07.928
So along came
the municipal bond,

07:07.961 --> 07:12.666
a big, fat IOU
that appeared to be salvation

07:12.700 --> 07:14.902
for a near-broke government.

07:14.935 --> 07:19.473
They're sexy for investors,
triple exempt from taxes,

07:19.507 --> 07:22.075
and bond owners
buying Puerto Rican debt

07:22.109 --> 07:27.948
would have to be paid back
before anyone.

07:27.981 --> 07:29.416
That's anyone.

07:29.449 --> 07:31.519
Hedge funds, or vulture funds,

07:31.552 --> 07:33.954
as they are often referred to
in these cases,

07:33.987 --> 07:36.790
had profited from
similarly desperate situations

07:36.824 --> 07:39.960
in Greece, Argentina,
and Detroit.

07:39.993 --> 07:42.496
As the situation worsened
for Puerto Rico,

07:42.530 --> 07:44.297
you could buy up
more and more bonds

07:44.331 --> 07:46.033
for pennies on the dollar.

07:46.066 --> 07:50.904
This was a fire sale
too sweet to pass up.

07:52.906 --> 07:55.375
And the resulting
insurmountable debt,

07:55.408 --> 07:58.445
it means drastic
austerity measures

07:58.478 --> 08:00.313
determined by an unelected board

08:00.347 --> 08:03.884
who have near absolute power
to raise taxes;

08:03.917 --> 08:05.886
empty teachers' pension plans;

08:05.919 --> 08:08.789
close down schools, hospitals;

08:08.822 --> 08:11.625
basically squeeze every dollar
out of Puerto Rico

08:11.659 --> 08:13.794
to pay back the funds.

08:13.827 --> 08:18.832
Every Puerto Rican is being
made to feel the pain.

08:20.734 --> 08:23.170
I mean, I know
schools are closing, yes?

08:23.203 --> 08:25.072
Last year, 240 schools closed.

08:25.105 --> 08:26.721
- Last year alone.
- In the last two years.

08:26.740 --> 08:28.709
This year, there's a list
of 300 schools

08:28.742 --> 08:31.645
that are "in risk"
of shutting down.

08:31.679 --> 08:33.179
Born in Puerto Rico?

08:33.212 --> 08:34.240
I was born in Chicago, Illinois.

08:34.246 --> 08:35.248
In Chicago.

08:35.282 --> 08:36.515
My family came back

08:36.549 --> 08:38.686
mostly because
our family was here.

08:38.719 --> 08:41.421
Puerto Ricans want the family
to stick together.

08:41.453 --> 08:43.756
If you can live
close to each other,

08:43.791 --> 08:44.925
the better.

08:44.958 --> 08:46.326
I decided to stay,

08:46.359 --> 08:48.896
because I wanted my kids
to grow up here.

08:48.929 --> 08:50.163
Better times.

08:50.197 --> 08:51.198
Better times, of course.

08:51.231 --> 08:52.532
What changed?

08:52.566 --> 08:54.702
The government took
too much in loans

08:54.735 --> 08:56.503
and couldn't pay them back.

08:56.536 --> 08:59.873
So they kept putting taxes
on the people,

08:59.907 --> 09:02.009
the working-class people
like me,

09:02.042 --> 09:04.377
and we cannot pay them.

09:04.411 --> 09:06.079
Like many professionals here,

09:06.113 --> 09:08.548
Liza-Marie Cordova
would probably have

09:08.582 --> 09:10.684
an easier time of it
in the States.

09:10.718 --> 09:12.586
But she chooses to stay.

09:12.620 --> 09:14.187
With the crisis
here in Puerto Rico,

09:14.221 --> 09:17.124
mostly I think about my kids.

09:17.157 --> 09:20.260
Will they have the options
to stay here

09:20.293 --> 09:24.665
and work and have a family?

09:29.136 --> 09:30.604
Okay, so where are we?

09:30.638 --> 09:32.773
We are at Casa Vieja in Ciales.

09:32.806 --> 09:37.410
This is a typical 1960, '50
grandmother's house.

09:37.444 --> 09:40.714
And the food is grandma food?

09:40.748 --> 09:43.383
It is grandma food, actually.

09:43.416 --> 09:45.786
Those are corn fritters
with ham.

09:45.819 --> 09:48.255
Typical Sunday
after Saturday party.

09:48.288 --> 09:49.489
Hangover food.

09:49.522 --> 09:50.590
Delicious.

09:50.624 --> 09:52.459
Thank you.

09:52.492 --> 09:54.261
So this is like a plantain soup.

09:54.294 --> 09:55.896
Mmm.
Ooh, that's good.

09:55.929 --> 09:58.598
The specialty here
is pastel al caldero,

09:58.632 --> 10:01.134
pork marinated in bitter orange,

10:01.168 --> 10:05.005
taro root, green plantains,
squash,

10:05.038 --> 10:08.575
and garbanzo beans slow cooked.

10:08.608 --> 10:12.279
And morcilla, blood sausage,

10:12.312 --> 10:14.915
one of my favorite things.

10:14.948 --> 10:16.616
Is good?

10:16.650 --> 10:18.852
It's fantastic.

10:18.886 --> 10:22.856
Teachers here are being asked
to pay into a pension system

10:22.890 --> 10:25.993
that has been described
as a Ponzi scheme.

10:26.026 --> 10:29.129
You pay 10% of your income
into your pension plan

10:29.162 --> 10:30.630
out of every paycheck.

10:30.664 --> 10:31.818
The money you're paying in now

10:31.832 --> 10:33.600
is being used to pay...

10:33.633 --> 10:35.057
The ones that are retired
right now.

10:35.068 --> 10:36.770
The ones who are
retiring right now:

10:36.804 --> 10:38.806
in a pyramid scheme,
the top of the pyramid.

10:38.839 --> 10:40.373
But by the time
it gets down to you,

10:40.407 --> 10:42.776
who've been paying in
for your entire life...

10:42.810 --> 10:44.277
There's no money left.

10:44.311 --> 10:45.679
I worry about my future.

10:45.713 --> 10:47.815
I don't know
what I'm gonna live off.

10:47.848 --> 10:51.151
I have two jobs
in order to pay my bills,

10:51.184 --> 10:54.221
have my car, have my house,
pay for my kids' education.

10:54.254 --> 10:55.655
Right.

10:55.689 --> 10:57.150
There's no way,
with one job as a teacher,

10:57.157 --> 10:58.225
I can do that.

10:58.258 --> 10:59.727
So how do you continue?

10:59.760 --> 11:02.562
I know I could get paid triple
in the States.

11:02.595 --> 11:04.631
But I don't want
to give up my country.

11:04.664 --> 11:07.500
My kids see
how their parents struggle.

11:07.534 --> 11:10.503
Things can change
if only one stands up

11:10.537 --> 11:12.172
and decides,
"I'm gonna do this."

11:12.205 --> 11:13.506
Right.

11:13.540 --> 11:15.035
But we have to empower
those children.

11:15.042 --> 11:18.011
We have to make them believe
they can change it,

11:18.045 --> 11:19.679
that there's a better life
for them.

11:19.713 --> 11:21.081
And I'm getting emotional,

11:21.114 --> 11:25.252
because sometimes I feel
that I've failed.

11:25.285 --> 11:27.520
I cannot save all of them.

11:27.554 --> 11:29.156
That's the truth.

11:29.189 --> 11:32.059
But I can save a lot,

11:32.092 --> 11:33.693
and that's my job.

11:33.727 --> 11:35.829
So that's what I'm going to do.

11:35.863 --> 11:37.230
I have hope.
I have faith.

11:37.264 --> 11:39.767
I'm taking a jump of faith.

